<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12031a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12031a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12031a"> 31(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> huguenote (flatchested) W / no homage to <u>saints</u></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Ne disait-on pas d&apos;une femme, dont la poitrine &eacute;tait plate, que c&apos;&eacute;tait une huguenote. Cette expression ou plut&ocirc;t cette comparaison intrigua longtemps les folkloristes; enfin l&apos;un d&apos;eux, plus avis&eacute;, fit remarquer &agrave; ses confr&egrave;res que les protestants ne rendaient pas aux saints le culte qui leur &eacute;tait d&ucirc;. Et voil&agrave;, du coup le surnom expliqu&eacute;! <br><font color="green">[Did one not say of a woman with a flat chest that she was a Huguenote. This expression, or better, this comparison, has intrigued the folklore specialists for a long time; finally one of them, slightly more intelligent, told his colleagues that the protestants did not render to the saints the veneration that was their due. And that explained the surname!]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 137</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>seins</i>, breasts, is homophonous with saints.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c12014m" href="c12all.htm#c12014m">VI.C.12:014(m)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
